Then `coroutine.start(start, coroutine, block)` tries to dispatch. When dispatch fails, `DispatchException` is thrown. But the `ProducerCoroutine` is still alive as a child!

Now back in `undispatchedResult`, we catch the exception and wrap it in `CompletedExceptionally(e)`. Then `makeCompletingOnce` is called. This tries to complete the `ScopeCoroutine` with the exception. But it needs to wait for children (the `ProducerCoroutine`), so it returns `COMPLETING_WAITING_CHILDREN`, and `undispatchedResult` returns `COROUTINE_SUSPENDED`.

